description.text:
This is a derivative work of the original Prusa 3D printer (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4148). The idea of metrix labs' pourable clonedel parts was good, but the parts have some technical shortfalls.
So I changed some parts into a pourable and working Prusa 3D printer. This is the result: The parts are like a standard reprap Prusa Mendel 3D printer. Most of the parts are pourable just the way they are. Only a few parts have too long holes inside or the walls are too thin - these parts had to be changed.
The affected parts: The XMotor, the XIdler and the 2 ZMotors, the vertices and some smaller parts like the barclamps and the endstop holders. The Vertices of a Prusa have about 2 mm wallthickness around the vertical holes. This seemed to be not enough for a casted part. So we made them stronger, but not as thick as Mendel vertices. The XMotor, XIdler and ZMotor have very long holes inside. We cut out at the side of the parts to split these long holes. Also the XMotor and the XIdler have large nut traps for capturing a spring.
These nut traps have been separated to a second part. This way the nut/spring trap keeps its function while being pourable. You can simply screw the two parts together. The clamps and the endstop holders have an increased wall thickness to provide more stability. The major advantage is: All the casted parts have already holes inside! We developed a special casting technique in which bridges act as spacers for the holes. In most cases this concept works perfect.
This reduces the amount of holes to be drilled to 10! The holes which are not pourable are the filament hole in the Wades extruder and the mounting holes in the small Wades gear and the pulleys.
All other holes are already in the casted part. The second advantage is: To prevent melting of the parts we used a special thermoresistant polyurethan instead of Smooth Cast 325.
After tempering the parts resist temperatures up to 120 Â°C. If you want to get more information visit: www.ifeelbeta.de I also mixed a making of video: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tf-F0O9J1nA&feature=player_embedded A video about the thermal resistance can be found here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V3zs0h04HIY You can buy a Set of these parts at: www.2printbeta.de I uploaded only a few parts as stl. All other parts can be found in the 7zip file. Greetings from the lake of constance
BonsaiBrain

Use SmoothOn Onyx Slow for all parts which are near a motor or the hotend.
Temper the parts to get improved thermal resistance.

This soffit vent fits in a 2.5" hole on the eave of a house. The soffit screens on my house were rusting through and birds were building nests in them.

It goes in the hole with just a friction fit. If it doesn't quite fit, adjust the "eave_hole_diameter" in the OpenScad file to resize. Also, if you use the OpenScad file, there are some settings for the print layer height, skin size and extrusion width that may help you get a better print. The settings I used were:
  • 0.25 layer height
  • 0.60 skin size
  • 0.5 extrusion width
    • I've included two versions of the vent. One has the screen recessed into the hole and the other has the screen flush with the hole. I thought the recessed one looked a little nicer. I picked red PLA to print it to match my front door.

The students would be able to learn the lobes of the brain by putting this puzzle together and justifying what each lobe is, the use of the lobe, and where it is located in relation to other parts of the brain. Audiences: Grades: 8-College; Age: 13+ Preparation:

Introduction First there was a need... the Ziks are great headphones but the battery life is a bit short, so a second battery comes handy. Parrot does not make a charger for a spare battery thus I decided to make one. The charger was partly designed on top of what I had at hand, the pogo pins. Pogo pins make really nice contacts but they need some nice housing to work well and that is what 3D printing really excels for, it is real easy to model a case around the battery and then add small holes for the pogos to go in. I also ordered up a few tp4056 chargers from eBay. Initially I started with just a 40x60x10mm block with a 8mm pocket for the battery and 1.5mm holes for the pogos (3). On the next version I dropped the middle pin, made the housing longer so there is no need to glue pins in as they seat agains outer rim. This also made suitable area for the charger PCB so I made a cutout for that. This basically finished the version 1. For version 2 I wanted to make it closed so I did some small tweaks so I can screw a cover for the charging PCB.. description.text:
The primary purpose of this attachment onto the Printrbot Simple 1401 model is to increase the overall height of the printer such that the electronics can be integrated under the body of the printer, and to increase the stability of the printer.  
Having modified my printer in the X & Y axis from the initial fishing string Dremmel sanding attachment drive to the GT2 belt with Jon Lawrence's conversion, and extending the Z axis height, I noticed stability issues with the printer.  Whenever the printer was in the homed X-axis position, the printer would want to tilt over rightwards (in terms of the front plane) due to the extra height and to the right-heavy design of the whole Y drive system and the extruder.  
As a solution to the issue of electronics integration and stabilization, I devised a method to add "shoe"-like pieces to the bottom of the printer that would slide on the balsa at the base.  Although it would raise the center of gravity of the whole printer, the fix would aid in increasing the stability by widening the effective footprint of the base.  
Below, shows the variations of the printer with, without, and the first iteration of the design for this set of problems.

title: Printrbot Simple 1401 - Fan Holder for Preheating Problems

description.text:
Until recently, I've ran across the issue that my printer would malfunction around forty to an hour into a print.  What would occur was that the filament would clog up so much so that it would gather into a giant blob right before it entered the body of the hot end, right at the point where the stepper motor of the extruder was pushing the filament in. 
I initially did not think much of this problem, only that it would be fine after I unclogged it after catching the problem right as I would hear knocking from the printer-extruder assembly.  Soon I realized that however, this problem was something that would cause problems later on and should be addressed as soon as possible.  
Researching online, I realized that this problem was due to "preheating" of the filament as it entered the warm/hot extruder assembly heated via conduction from running the motor extended periods of time.  I tried to fix the problem via using nylon spacers in between the motor and aluminum extruder assembly, hoping that this would remedy the problem.  This only merely extended my window of failure to one hour +/- thirty minutes.  
Finally, I concluded that it would be a better idea to simply use the fan motor that I had originally removed from the printer as a method of cooling down the extruder assembly.  After this attachment, I've ran 4+ hour prints without any problems.  
A simple part has made all the difference in the effectiveness of the printer.

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://tinkercad.com/things/gt9KGMuMHGv The brackets screw directly to the wall and a plug will hide the screw hole. The brackets fit an aluminum extrusion in which a LED strip is fastened down. It is driven by a 12V DC supply, a used power brick can be used for that.

These brackets will hold an aluminum tube with LED strip onto a wall and light up the wall. Screw connection on both and electrical provisions on one. Mount top bracket first, then push in the tube , mount bottom bracket so it just slips in. The tube will then descent but still be captured by the top bracket. The profile is PDS-O series Klus Profile Housing PDS-O from SuperbrightLEDS.
http://www.superbrightleds.com/moreinfo/housings/pds-o-series-o-shape-aluminum-led-profile-housing-pds-o/988/2404/ The picture shows how I put two of these in the bedroom on either side of the bed. It replaces the bed lights. There is another string of LEDs on the back of the bed as well. To operate the lights I have two microswitches in an enclosure Thing:109056. They are attached to an Arduino that operates all three lights. Either switch will on the first click light both side lights, second click adds the light behind the bed, third click turns off the side lights and last click makes everything dark again. I can upload the Arduino code as well if there is interest in it.
In the micro enclosure there is room for a digistump that could replace the Arduino, thus making the whole a little bit tidier. http://digistump.com/products/1

New version 2.0 added.. Better Fit and stronger 2014 Hyundai Sonata Cel Phone Bracket

title: Jabra Solemate Holder for Beach Cruiser

description.text:
I really love my Jabra Solemate bluetooth speaker. Since I live at the beach, I spend a LOT of time on various beach cruisers but mainly two beach cruisers that both use a similar double downtube frame design.  
If you have a beach cruiser that uses a similar design, and you also have a Jabra Solemate, you probably need this design. If you don't have a Jabra Solemate, this design will make you want to go out and buy one.   
This is my 2nd attempt at a speaker holder for the bike. The first version clamped on to the top tube and it put the center of gravity for the speaker way too high. This new design is MUCH stronger, and it keeps the speaker down low and more protected. After some quick tests on the cruiser, this thing just works and it's very solid.

I've included the STL for the base that holds the speaker and two different lower mounts. I have a firmstrong cruiser and an electra crusier. Both of these use different downtube diameter/spacing. If you don't have a firmstrong or electra cruiser, you'll need to edit the scad file and put in your own values. It's pretty easy. I print the top with lots of infill since I also tap it with a 1/4"x20 tap. The rest of the parts I print with 10% infill. Also, make sure your upper mount uses a rise of 9mm so there is clearance for the thumb bolts and they don't hit the frame of your cruiser. For a complete unit you'll need to print: Top
Base
(2) mounts (an upper and lower)
(6) Thumb Bolts You'll need to buy: (2) 1/4"x20 Hex Nuts
(4) 1/4"x20 Hex Bolts, 1" long You'll also need to tap the holes for the bolts. Happy cruising.

Durer's polyhedra from "Melancholia" is usually though to be a cube stretched along a three fold axis and truncated by planes at right angles to the stretched axis, one above and one below the center of the cube. An angle on one of the faces, called the apex, is used to describe the polyhedra; it falls from 90 degrees as the amount of stretching increases. Thing:105351 is such a polyhedra. Here are two more versions of the polyhedra - one by D.I. McCooey - http://dmccooey.com/polyhedra/Durer.html - with an apex angle of 77.14 degrees and one from Wolfram - http://mathworld.wolfram.com/DuerersSolid.html - with an apex angle of 72 degrees. OpenSCAD code is provided.

Durer_wolfram.scad is a good example of the ease of use of openSCAD.  The recipe given on the Wolfram web page was transferred to a few lines of openSCAD code. The code can be easily modified to make other versions of the polyhedra.

description.text: Chris Chafin

Here's a remix of Noudje's spool holder. I adjusted it to use M5 screws and roller bearings which are 14x5x5. Linked below are the bearing I purchased for this project. The M5 screws I acquired from Ace Hardware, and as such, any major store like that should carry some. http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B008X18PNC?psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00 Each wheel houses two bearings on either side, so you'll need 8 bearings in total. Noudje's base design for the spool holder; I find it one of the best designs for adding the spool holder on top. It gives the filiment spool a nice smooth action to roll on, rather than the rough action it'd have on a typical spool holder that is composed of 2 support structures and a bar in between. There's only one other one I found that'd match in quality of design, however, it's also a little more complex in it's setup. Best yet is the offset, which has the filament coming down in a straighter line, rather than bent in like spool holders that house it directly above the slot. With filament that is more delicate, it's a must. It'll lead the filament off the spool in a more natural position.
